AGI - Air raids and clashes continue in the Gaza Strip, despite a first United Nations resolution of the previous day calling for an immediate " ceasefire" in the Palestinian territory, raising the ires of Israel. At the beginning of Tuesday, some witnesses reported attacks near Rafah, a city at the southern end of the Gaza Strip where 1.5 million Palestinians are massed, most of them displaced due to violence in the rest of the territory, the scene of a deadly war between Hamas and Israel for almost six months. According to the Israeli army, missile alarms were launched around Gaza.
&nbsp;
On Monday, for the first time since the war, the United Nations Security Council adopted a resolution calling for a " ceasefire", with 14 votes in favour and abstention, the United States. Israel's long-standing ally, Washington had previously opposed the use of the term "fire" in UN resolutions, blocking three texts of this type.
&nbsp;
The text "requires an immediate ceasefire for the month of Ramadan" - started fifteen days ago - that it should "bring to a lasting ceasefire", and "requires the immediate and unconditional release of all hostages". The failure to implement this resolution would be "unforgivable", said UN Secretary-General Antonio Guterres after the vote, hailed by the main capitals.
