AGI - At four months of the Paris Olympic Games 2024 the climate is already overheating in the French capital, scene of protests to denounce racism, social marginalization, discrimination and threats to the environment. Tens of anti-racist militants of 'SOS Racisme' danced in front of the headquarters of the National Group (RN), the extreme right party of the leader Marine le Pen. To light the protests was the reaction of Le Pen, strongly opposed to the idea that the French-Malian singer Aya Nakamura can participate in the opening ceremony, on July 26. For the right-wing leader, with his proposal President Emmanuel Macron wants to "divide" and "humiliar" the French. Nakamura is the most listened French singer in the world since the release of his hit 'Djadja' in 2018, but since he came out that he could play songs by Edith Piaf, he is victim of racist attacks.
To contest his participation, Le Pen criticized the fact that "not sings in French", his "volgarity" and the "mode of dressing". What an answer, yesterday a group of militants staged a dance to the sound of the music of Nakamura and Piaf. "We are preparing to welcome the whole world for the Olympics, and there is a controversy because some want to symbolically postpone - and not only symbolically - our greatest French artist in Bamako," said Dominique Sopo, president of 'SOS Racisme'.
