AGI -&nbsp; Harris' eagles and hawks to hunt more and more numerous and annoying pigeons, pushing them to take refuge in the parks: This is the strategy of the city of Barcelona to counter the colonies of birds that disturb the activities at Camp Nou, the football field of FC Barcelona, and the neighboring condominiums. The Guardian reports it, specifying that at the moment it is an experimental project> to try to control the population of urban pigeons.
&nbsp;
After results so far unsuccessful, three-four teams of raptors with the 'mission' &nbsp; patrol the area around the Camp Nou, between 8 and 16. The pigeons that nested in the ground were cast out from the construction works and moved into the neighboring condominiums, whose residents asked for an intervention. The idea is to bring pigeons to nearby parks where they will be less annoying.
&nbsp;
"The raptors can also eat some pigeons, but that's not the idea. And then a dead pigeon does not learn," said Albert Tomàs, spokesman of the company responsible for performing the job. Promising the outcome of the first test: the only view of the eagles in low altitude flight was enough to disturb the pigeons, who received the message of having to leave. If the Camp Nou pilot project is successful, it will be extended to other areas of Barcelona. At the same time, a campaign was launched to prevent people from throwing food on the street, a behaviour that encourages the growth of the population of pigeons. This new strategy was conceived after a previous failed attempt to control a population of about 85 thousand, which consisted of adding a contraceptive to their food. In some areas, such as Placa de Catalunya in the city center, the concentration of birds is double compared to the recommended one. In 2017 the capital of Catalonia had already successfully used raptors to disperse flocks of pigeons that were damaging the roof of the Palau Sant Jordi concert hall. Most Spanish airports already use falcons to discourage bird attacks which, according to estimates, cost the global airline industry $12 billion a year. Barcelona Airport has a team of 80 hawks, while about 70 pilgrim hawks patrol the Madrid Barajas airport.

